description.plain:
Will Toledo is an upstanding young man who has upheld the letter of the law to the fullest extent of his abilities.

He passed through his school years and through college without any evidence of criminal wrongdoings being attached to him, indeed becoming a role model and a guiltless beacon of hope to his peer group, members of whom might have otherwise been terribly misled.

He has no identifying marks or scars.

Will works as a writer and performer for the band Car Seat Headrest, building the band from the ground up. He started off recording vocals in his car and now is an indie sensation. He should not be arrested under any circumstances.

songs.full_title: Drunk Drivers/Killer Whales by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Drunk Drivers/Killer Whales

description.plain:
On the Matador Records blog, songwriter Will Toledo says the song is about “post-party melancholia. Wishing to either be a better person or care less about the whole deal. Going home alone, in poor condition. The ‘killer whales’ bit is inspired by Blackfish, which is a depressing film.”

A shorter rework of the song was later released as a single.

songs.full_title: Fill in the Blank by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Fill in the Blank

description.plain:
“Fill in the Blank” is the opening track to Car Seat Headrest’s 2016 album, Teens of Denial.

The song introduces several of the key themes on the album, mainly the antagonistic, self-loathing relationship someone struggling with depression can develop, and the complicated relationships they can have with others as a result.

description.plain: Despite barely touching the stuff himself, Will Toledo poses a morose look at how and why we cope with substance abuse on “Drugs With Friends”.  Of the drugs referenced on Teens of Denial, he’s said “I’ve smoked weed a half dozen times and it’s always made me anxious. [Denial] is a very sober album, which is funny, because it does talk about drugs a lot”.

description.plain: The penultimate track on Twin Fantasy (Face to Face), it is arguably the most changed track from the original Mirror to Mirror recording. It incorporates elements of “Unfinished: Pain Star (If heaven is full of people…”, a Mirror to Mirror outtake that was previously released on the b-sides album Disjecta Membra. In the Face to Face liner notes, “Famous Prophets” is subtitled “A Song About Jesus.”

description.plain:
The picture is from the included lyric sheet.

Beach Life-In-Death is the longest song on the album, clocking in at 12 minutes, 11 seconds.  The song changes style a few times throughout the song, and the lyric sheet separates the song into three parts.

The title is presumably a reference to Samuel Taylor Coleridge’s poem “Rime of the Ancient Sea Mariner”, in which a character known as Life-in-Death appears to curse the mariner for his sins.

songs.title: The Ballad of the Costa Concordia
songs.title_with_featured: The Ballad of the Costa Concordia

description.plain: The Costa Concordia was a cruise ship that sank in 2012 within hours of having just left port. In this song, Will compares what he sees as his immediate failure to adjust to adult life at his young age to the failures of the ship’s captain sinking within hours of departure, asking “how was I supposed to know how to steer the ship?” The song is structured in three major parts: a slow, balladic introduction, a figurative confessional breakdown (featuring an interpolation of Dido’s 2003 single “White Flag”), and a literal instrumental breakdown followed by a triumphant declaration of surrender.

And what about a vacation to feel good?

How was I supposed to know?
And God won’t forgive me

And how am I supposed to do that
When I go to this same room every night
And sleep in the same bed every night?
The same fucking bed
With the red comforter with the white stripes

I give up

[Verse 3]

We wanted control too, but that was normal
'Cause our life was one of survival
The decisions we've made, if you can call it deciding
With your life on the line, it'd be social suicide to change your mind
So we got mad and we split the scene
Now we download all of our shit for free
It's the new economy, we have nothing to offer and we sleep on trash

[Chorus]
I give up
I give up
[Verse 4]
Let us take you back to where you came in
A man clinging to the cliff of revelation
So scared of what he would find, he started crying
"It was not me"
Stopped at the borderline, they stripped his disguise
So he read a book that won a Pulitzer prize
It was about death, it didn't help
He saw himself in it

And he was disturbed at the conclusions it led to
But he couldn't say what because the author was dead too
And so though he made fun of us
He has now become one of us

[Chorus]
I give up
I give up
I give up
I give up

I give up
I give up
I give up

songs.full_title: Vincent by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Vincent

description.plain:
“Vincent” is the second track and debut single from Car Seat Headrest’s 2016 album, Teens of Denial.

Named after the Dutch artist, Vincent Van Gogh, singer/songwriter Will Toledo described the song as being about “fighting to hold one’s place in the crowd, to hold one’s drink. It’s about shouting to be heard, but what’s the point, no one’s saying anything worth listening to. It’s about wanting to leave but not wanting to go home. The music is too loud.”

description.plain:
Like the rest of the content on this album, this song is a “re-recorded re-imagined” version of the 2011 version.

There are some lyrical changes, replacing Dan Bejar and John Entwistle with Frank Ocean and James Brown. Toledo also removed a reference to Stanley Kubrick and “Eyes Wide Shut” from the outro.

As the seventh track (and the last before the decidedly mood changing “High to Death”), “Cute Thing” is more of an energetic straightforward power pop song. Bereft of existential themes (as was the case with “Bodys”), “Cute Thing” is, ironically, on the whole (with the exception of the darkly foretelling “Lemme light your cigarette”) even more romantic.

songs.full_title: Not What I Needed by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Not What I Needed

description.plain:
When Teens of Denial was first announced, this track was known as “Just What I Needed/Not Just What I Needed,” featuring heavily interpolated elements from the Cars' iconic power pop song “Just What I Needed.” While the album was initially cleared to include the “samples,” a legal snafu a week before Teens of Denial’s release resulted in the license being revoked, the outro overhauled, and the physical versions of the record (which, by this point, had already been shipped out to distributors) recalled.

The resulting rework, “Not What I Needed,” has a new ending featuring a reversed sample of the Teens of Style version of “Something Soon” and an audio clip of Will stumbling through a choppy interview with a German radio station.

Despite the crisis, Will told MTV, “I like it better than the original version.”

That was my least favorite song on the album already. It was the least emotionally engaging to me. It seemed kind of smug and sarcastic in a way that I didn’t really want to pursue. This changed the tone of it and brought some more emotions to the surface.

“1937 State Park” is the seventh track off of Car Seat Headrest’s album “Teens Of Denial”. It is probably the most guitar heavy rock song on the album, and also features a cool organ solo.

The title of the song refers to a handwritten note  found on the photo that is used on the album cover (the same photo is mentioned midway through the song).

songs.full_title: I Want You to Know That I’m Awake/i Hope That You’re Asleep by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: I Want You to Know That I’m Awake/i Hope That You’re Asleep
songs.title_with_featured: I Want You to Know That I’m Awake/i Hope That You’re Asleep

description.plain: This song is about a relationship in which, due to internal and external factors, one of the people in the relationship (Will Toledo, in this instance) is unable to communicate their emotions in any effective way. The first half of the song details Will’s feelings around this issue and later, an argument that led him to flee from his significant other, hiding in his car in the parking lot of a grocery store. The second half of the song lists a number of other failed relationships, each of them followed by Will reassuring himself/his significant other that they won’t find an end similar to the relationships of the people he lists.

songs.full_title: Maud Gone by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Maud Gone

description.plain:
“Maud Gone” is the 7th track on Car Seat Headrest’s 2012 album Monomania, and the 8th track on 2015’s Teens of Style. The song is named after Irish revolutionary, Maud Gonne, the unrequited love and muse of poet William Butler Yeats.



Despite never officially being released as a single, “Maud Gone” has become one of the most popular tracks off Teens of Style, regularly being played at live shows.

songs.title: Kimochi Warui (When? When? When? When? When? When? When?)
songs.title_with_featured: Kimochi Warui (When? When? When? When? When? When? When?)

description.plain:
In the third track of How to Leave Town, Will realizes that all the heroes and idols he’s respected for his entire life are a sham, and finds himself in a bit of an existential crisis. In Japanese, the phrase “kimochi warui” has no direct English translation but is synonymous with a feeling for disgust or hatred.

The title may be a direct reference to the 1997 anime film, The End of Evangelion, which serves as a finale to the television show that preceded it. In the final, symbolic scene of the film, Asuka utters this phrase after Shinji tries to strangle her.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pVeKyqV1jWU

songs.lyrics:
Hey Will, why don’t you cut the shit
And tell me who you’re fighting for?
If you’re not taking care of yourself
Then what are you here for?

I used to think there was an answer
In the music of my youth
But I just read Brian Wilson’s biography
And now I know the truth
Because his father never loved him
And the band just wanted the money
And Dennis was an alcoholic
Who drowned looking for treasure
And everyone who was around him
Just gave him drugs and took his money
He was dependent on social acceptance
Just like every other human
And now I’ve got no one to pray to
And now I’ve got nowhere to stay the night
And it’s hard to be here at all

I have no faith in life to leave me satisfied
I’ll have these doubts and worries until the day I die
And I will not go to heaven and I will not go to hell
I have no faith in death to be anything at all
(I feel sick
I don't feel well
What a disgusting feeling
I don't like this feeling
How disgusting
This feeling sucks)
Some of these things are symptoms
And some of these are being human
And now I'm torn between
Trying to be a better man
And trying to accept the man I am
The people that I’ve talked to
And the books that I’ve read
And the TV shows and movies that I’ve seen

Are all I have to turn to
To learn how to live
But when? When? When? When?
When? When? When will I ever learn?7EmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

songs.full_title: Can't Cool Me Down by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Can’t Cool Me Down

description.plain:
“Can’t Cool Me Down” is an electronic indie pop song about performance anxiety and not being able to portray one’s authentic self in front of people.

Like other songs from the album, Toledo collaborates on the track with Car Seat Headrest drummer Andrew Katz, as the electronic side project dubbed 1 Trait Danger, with Toledo playing his alternate persona, “Trait.”

On the Car Seat Headrest Bandcamp page, Toledo provides background on the song and expands on the song’s topic of the extreme nervousness he experiences while playing onstage:

Bob Dylan said, ‘if someone’s wearing a mask, he’s gonna tell you the truth…if he’s not wearing a mask, it’s highly unlikely.’ He never actually wore a mask onstage so I don’t know why he said that. But I decided to start wearing a mask for a couple of reasons. One, I still get nervous being onstage with everybody looking at me. If everyone is looking at the mask instead, then it feels like we’re all looking at the same thing, and that is more honest to me. Two, music should be about enjoying yourself, especially live music, and I think of this costume as a way to remind myself and everyone else to have some fun with it. I don’t think it changes anything else about the songs or how you feel about them to be able to drop it for a second and have fun with it. If you can’t do that then you’re in a bad place… The character comes from another project Andrew and I have been working on called 1 TRAIT DANGER… I play a character called TRAIT, and we’ve been working out the backstory as we go. I think he spent a lot of time in classified government facilities before getting into the music business.

“Can’t Cool Me Down” is the first single to be released off the album Making a Door Less Open.

songs.full_title: The Gun Song by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: The Gun Song

description.plain:
In an album full of “long, dense, layered songs that no one liked”, The Gun Song is the longest (actually, it’s the longest song Will’s recorded to date, clocking in at a daunting 16:05), densest, and layered…est. Despite this, The Gun Song is immediately memorable, brimming with one-liners equally witty and poignant.

It could also be theorized that this is the final song in the “Twin Fantasy Saga”, consisting of the “Beach” songs from 3, Twin Fantasy, and Monomania based off of the lyrical content and the reference to both Stop Smoking and [Los Borrachos] (http://carseatheadrest.tumblr.com/post/78125200262/theres-time-for-one-more-tonight-reference-to), as well as the general theme of [love and death]http://carseatheadrest.tumblr.com/post/78125081021/the-gun-song-key-g-major-structure-part-i .

songs.full_title: Stop Smoking (We Love You) by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Stop Smoking (We Love You)

description.plain:
The third song of the re-recorded version of CSH’s Twin Fantasy, and one of only a handful that sees none, or very few changes instrumentally or lyrically.

One of the easier songs to interpret, Stop Smoking (We Love You) is Will telling his partner to simply stop smoking. On a grander scale, this song is important as it introduces Will’s partner’s smoking habit as a device for Will to explore his conflicting feelings towards the relationship (most notably through the contrast created between the overprotective-ness shown in these lyrics and the desperate/accepting nature of those on High to Death where “Stop smoking” becomes “Keep smoking”).

songs.full_title: No Passion by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: No Passion

description.plain:
“No Passion” was originally recorded with different lyrics as “no passion” on Car Seat Headrest’s 2011 album My Back Is Killing Me Baby.

The song describes feelings of deadness and coldness – the narrator is disillusioned and feels that he has been damaged or dulled.

The title is an allusion to the Talking Heads song “No Compassion”.

songs.full_title: Anchorite (Love You Very Much) by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Anchorite (Love You Very Much)

description.plain:
This song is an emotional, 14-minute closer to this album.

An anchorite is a person who withdraws from society and becomes a recluse for religious reasons.

Given the title of the album being Monomania, which means an obsessive preoccupation with one single thing, and the recurring theme of failed love, it is possible that Will has become an “anchorite”, due to his obsession with this one person’s loss of affection for him.

songs.full_title: Joe Goes to School by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Joe Goes to School

description.plain:
According to Spin.com, “Toledo continued to write, usually while doing everyday things like biking through colonial Williamsburg to get to class during his senior year at William & Mary. From there, he got the gentle album closer ‘Joe Goes to School’ — one of the many points where his mononym’d alter ego appears. Toledo explains he first found ‘Joe’ by Googling the phrase ‘Teens of Denial’ to ensure no one else had already used it as an album title. One of the first results was this About.com article on dealing with teenagers who are in denial — [the song title] ‘(Joe Gets Kicked Out of School for Using) Drugs With Friends’ was a direct quote from that article.”

…

“The other ‘Joe’ song, ‘Joe Goes to School,’ that title came when one of my friends was trying to remember the title of ‘Drugs With Friends,‘ he explains. He was like, ‘And that one song, ‘Joe Goes to School.’ And I’m like, ‘That’s not the title at all, but I like that.’”

http://www.spin.com/2016/03/car-seat-headrest-teens-of-denial-interview/

songs.full_title: Hollywood by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Hollywood

description.plain:
“This song is about Hollywood as a place where people go to make their fantasies come to life, and they end up exploiting other people and doing terrible things to maintain their fantasy. There’s this terror you’re going to lose the fantasy, and you’re going to have to face the facts, and some people will do anything to avoid facing that. It’s about that fear, and the pain of being subjugated to someone else’s fantasy against your will, and it’s all tied together under this banner of this physical location of Hollywood that we all know about and dream about, but none of us really want to think about what is going on behind the scenes there.”
-Will Toledo on “Hollywood”

songs.full_title: Weightlifters by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Weightlifters

description.plain:
“Weightlifters” is the opening track to Car Seat Headrest’s twelfth album, Making A Door Less Open.

Originally written in 2015, it is the oldest song on the album. In an interview with Entertainment Weekly, Toledo described the track by saying:

I think a lot of this album is different physical states. “Weightlifters” is wanting to get out of the lethargy of an aging body, wanting to fine-tune things into a progressive state. And then the rest of the album is a counter against that. It really goes back and forth.

songs.title_with_featured: Los Borrachos (I Don't Have Any Hope Left, but the Weather Is Nice)

description.plain:
“Los Borrachos (I Don’t Have Any Hope Left, but the Weather Is Nice)” is the 5th track on 2012’s Monomania and the 9th track on 2015’s Teens of Style. The title is spanish for “The Drunks”, and is a reference to the painting “The Triumph of Bacchus (Los Borrachos)” by Diego Velázquez.

“Los Borrachos” has close ties with a few other Car Seat Headrest songs, mainly “Souls” (which opens with a reversed sample of the song’s outro) and “Endpiece” (an alternative version of the breakdown)

description.plain: The original version of the Teens of Denial song, Not What I Needed. This song features a sample of Just What I Needed by The Cars, an American rock band led by Ric Ocasek. The sample wasn’t authorized by Ric, even after physical copies of the album had been printed. Those LPs to be destroyed and Will had to rewrite the song without the sample or references, creating Not What I Needed.

This works as a sort of “Where Are They Now?”, chronicling the events that occured post Twin Fantasy.

songs.full_title: Drunk Drivers/Killer Whales (Single Version) by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Drunk Drivers/Killer Whales (Single Version)

description.plain:
Though the album version was critically lauded upon its release, its six-minute runtime and winding song structure prevented it from achieving mainstream radio dominance. This re-recorded version cuts the runtime in half but keeps the jangly hooks of the original, along with a Pavement-recalling intro and a new outro cribbed from a deep Car Seat cut.

The new arrangement was premiered on the December 1, 2016 edition of The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon and officially released the next morning.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EX00R_-Eh0I

description.plain:
“Dreams Fall Hard” is the 14th track on Nervous Young Man. It marks a strong shift in tone from the previous, far more energetic tracks, “I Wanna Sweat” and “Burning Man” before ending on a bleak piano solo.

The song mainly deals with themes of heartbreak and coming out.

songs.full_title: Plane Crash Blues (I Can't Play the Piano) by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Plane Crash Blues (I Can’t Play the Piano)
songs.title_with_featured: Plane Crash Blues (I Can't Play the Piano)

description.plain:
“Plane Crash Blues (I Can’t Play the Piano)” is a somber song, but makes a very strong melodic shift towards its end, one that was most likely the inspiration for the melodic change after the breakdown in “The Ballad of the Costa Concordia.” The content of the lyrics of “Plane Crash Blues” goes for a more depressive, sadder tone until this melodic change,  where the tone becomes much more determined and reassuring, as the narrator attempts to convince himself that he can get through the problems that ail him.

Its name implies that it is the companion song to “I Can Play the Piano,” another somber song off of the same album that comes earlier in the tracklist.

songs.full_title: Homes by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Homes

description.plain:
This gist of this song is about an abusive relationship, and how truly escaping from it feels impossible.

Will uses the idea of a home as the relationship, mentioning how it is almost falling apart, and how neither can “go home” as they live together. They could go to bed, but as the chorus mentions, both lovers get in physical fights, almost split, but then go to sleep and wake up late at the end of the day. He goes on to even mention the idea of leaving the house together that is falling apart, showing how him and his lover never separated even when the house was clearly falling apart. It could also mean “go out tonight” as going out to eat,  as the home is either too poor or too broken to make meals. He also mentions “If home is where I go to die”, which goes against the idea of a home being a safe place.

This is not a healthy lifestyle, and Will touches on the fear of never changing, or never leaving the home in the post-chorus. Bit and pieces like the piano in Verse 1 are mentioned, meaning part of each lover that was moved into the home, or rather the relationship

Whether this is all a large metaphor could be looked into deeper, but it could also be in the literal sense.

songs.full_title: What's With You Lately by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: What’s With You Lately

description.plain:
The only (or at least the first) Car Seat Headrest song where Ethan Ives is the lead vocalist. Will Toledo justified his choice to let Ethan sing it in this interview.
He states that he always thought that song was for Ethan and that he wanted live performances where each member could be in the spotlight. He also notes that “when Ethan sings that song, it leaves the frame of my mind and gives the listener a different perspective. It feels like a chorus in an ancient Greek play. It’s not a story told by the protagonist, but a narration.”

(note: I do not speak Japanese so I had to assume that the original meaning of the quote was kept intact by google)

songs.full_title: Beach Funeral by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Beach Funeral

description.plain:
The character who will sings about in twin fantasy and in beach fagz is “dead” because they are already in a relationship with someone else. Maybe they are ‘dead-to’ Will or maybe they are just unreachable now.

On beach life-in-death Will mentions that he wrote this song “when I knew you were taken”, so I think it’s safe to assume that he fell in love with the subject of twin fantasy before they got together and when this person was already in a relationship, producing an emotionally charged song about unrequited love.

songs.full_title: Some Strange Angel by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Some Strange Angel

description.plain:
“Some Strange Angel” is the 19th and penultimate track on Nervous Young Man.

It was originally intended to be the final song on the album, before “Knife in the Coffee” was added. Will has since noted on Bandcamp that “the final two tracks are not meant to be in any particular order; choose whichever sequencing suits your needs the best.”

songs.full_title: Ivy (Frank Ocean Cover) by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Ivy (Frank Ocean Cover)

description.plain:
This song is the eighth track on Car Seat headrest’s 2019 Live album, ‘Commit Yourself Completely’.

description.plain:
An alternate mix of the song (“March Mix”) was released on Bandcamp on August 4, 2017, as part of Bandcamp’s donation drive for the Transgender Law Center. It was available for one day only and accompanied by art by Remy Boydell.



The title and chorus allude to John Lennon’s “Happy Xmas (War Is Over)” and its refrain: “War is over if you want it.”

songs.full_title: I Can Play the Piano by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: I Can Play the Piano

description.plain:
“I Can Play the Piano” is the 10th track on Car Seat Headrest’s 2013 album, Nervous Young Men. The title, along with “Plane Crash Blues (I Can’t Play the Piano)”, possibly reference a childhood experience of Toledo’s:

“My dad thought I knew how to read music, so he kept giving me pieces to play, but what I was doing was just listening to him play and then trying to imitate it myself, and that got harder and harder as the pieces got harder and harder until eventually I just broke down crying one day at the piano, and it all came out that I didn’t know how to read music… I think it’s indicative of my personality that even as a child I would hide my weaknesses from everyone as long as I could.”

From Will Toledo:

removed from 5, maybe unjustly, but I had a long song prepared for the second to last slot on Twin Fantasy and this was the second to last song on 5 and I didn’t want it to become A Thing.

There’s also a early demo version of this song known as Teenage Night, which features different lyrics as well as Will talking about a game he played at a friends house.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AjFtW-SMXBQ

songs.lyrics:
[Verse 1]
I think you could be beautiful
I wouldn't love you if you were
Eyes the size of light bulbs
Irises sharpie dots
Sometimes I think you're beautiful
I don't love you when you are
Every other day like this
Alone on the bedroom floor

[Pre-Chorus 1]
Let's stare each other in the face
Don't tell me we are not in space
The rags we started out with
The rags we ended up with
I'll text you walking on your legs
I'll need to see you when I'm dead
I said you know that when we kiss
It's never on the lips so

[Chorus]
You can talk
You can talk
You can talk!
You can talk!
[Verse 2]
Sometimes a cigarette
Is just a phallic symbol
I've come up sporting half a haircut
That scissors couldn't fix
And sometimes a cigarette
Is just a good way to die
My legs around your back
I just needed words to sing

[Pre-Chorus 2]
Never look me in the eye
Cause yours see so much more than mine
The rags with which we started out
The rags with which we ended up
You walk with spine curved backwards
I'd like to meet your actor
I can't get to sleep until I know
For sure that you've moved on

[Chorus]

You can talk!

You can talk!
You can talk!3EmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

songs.lyrics:
I think I'm about to be pissed
You guys, left me here. Driving around in this town I have no fucking idea how to get around in. Never been here before. Never driven here before. You said I could park here. I can't fucking park here because there's a towzone. So now I'm just driving around, I don't know where the fuck I'm going, I'm already fucking up. Where th-Where th-WHERE THE FUCK DID YOU GUYS GO? WHY ARE ALL THESE ONE WAY STREETS? JESUS! FUCK THIS TOWN!
YOU'VE BEEN ON METH THE WHOLE NIGHT? YOU FUCKING CUNT! I THOUGHT WE WERE BONDING BUT, BUT YOU WERE ON METH! WE WERE HAVING A GOOD TIME, GETTING TO KNOW EACH OTHER AND THEN I LOOK AT YOUR EYES AND YOU'RE FUCKING TWEAKING! I DIDN'T EVEN WANT THIS DRINK! WHY DO I HAVE THIS DRINK? JESUS, DID YOU PUT SOMETHING IN IT? YOU FUCKING SOCIOPATH!
WHY D-WHY DID YOU TAKE METH? I SWEAR TO GOD, I'M LEAVING AFTER THIS DRINK

I FELL OFF MY BIKE
I'M DRUNK ON A WORK NIGHT
WHY DID I LET YOU IN
WHY DID I LET YOU IN1EmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

songs.title: God Save The Queen

songs.lyrics:
[Verse 1]
It’s hard to adjust your eyes after the matinee
From the womb of the theater to the light of day
But you’ve got something to think about on the ride home
And you’ve got something to talk about if you’re not alone

[Pre-Chorus 1]
Outside the walls I hear sirens
Fade to black, dramatic irony
Before my eyes, after the previews
I can relate, you do what we do
So I’m alive in the final act
The spirits did it all in an hour and a half
Bring me to pain, bring me to relief
Turn off my brain, suspend my disbelief

[Chorus]
There’s a beautiful score I’ll never hear
When my vision blurs, it rings in my ears
I must be saved
I must be saved before the end
There’s a wonderful line I can’t remember
I can’t rewind, so I better remember
I must be saved
I must be saved before the end
[Verse 2]
The hero stands up and the blood rushes out of his head
But you can still see him breathing after he’s dead
And after the soul is gone, his body’s back to himself
And you’ll say “Oh, who is he? I've seen him in something else”

[Pre-Chorus 2]
And so I pray to the movie screen
That I’ll be shown something I’ve never seen
A revelation, I can sense it
But this part don’t make any sense yet
If heaven is a film that never ends
And the characters are all my friends
Or is that what we call a tv show?
Or is that the real life that we’re living now?

[Chorus]
There’s a beautiful score I’ll never hear
When my vision blurs, it rings in my ears
I must be saved
I must be saved before the end
There’s a wonderful line I can’t remember
I can’t rewind so I better remember
I must be saved
I must be saved before the end
[Bridge]
Everyone left the theater
Everyone left the theater
Everyone left the theater
Everyone but me

[Chorus]
There’s a beautiful score I’ll never hear
When my vision blurs it rings in my ears
I must be saved
I must be saved
I must be saved

[Outro]
Could’ve been better, had such potential
Could’ve been better, had such potential
Could’ve been better, had such potential
Could’ve been better, had such potential
Yeah, yeah

(God save our gracious Queen
Long live our noble Queen
God save the Queen
Send her victorious
Happy and glorious
Long to reign over us
God save the Queen)EmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

description.plain:
“And rounding off the release is Car Seat Headrest, who since the planning of this release have gone stratospheric. First coming to our attention with the release of their 2013 album Nervous Young Man (seriously one of the greatest albums of the 21st century), they followed it up with How To Leave Town the following year. Featured on this release is an alternate take on America from that album, along with the unreleased Culture from around that time.”

songs.title: The Hard Part

description.plain:
This song contains the same chord progression as the outro to “Sober to Death” off of Twin Fantasy, as well as lyrical nods to that very song and “Souls” off of Monomania.

This song heavily implies the narrator is going through a break up and shares similar themes displayed throughout Monomania (heart break, partying, neurotic behavior)

body.plain: A recount of Will having to clean people’s lawns, a true occurrence on the cold day of 27th December 2010.

songs.lyrics:
December 27th: my dad walked in
I was 18 years old
He said "our trash can's blown over
The trash is all scattered across other people's lawns"
So I put on a jacket and I forgot my gloves
We went outside
It was cold as fuck

(I keep seeing these things out of the corner of my eye)

He gave me a trash bag, pointed across the street
Our trash was everywhere
So we went at it like an Easter egg hunt
Always more to be found
The wind started blowing
Every time I took my hands out of my fucking pockets
Shove 'em back in again

Bags from Kohl's and Target
Different colored gift wrap and thousands of receipts
I walked from lawn to lawn
I skipped the ones with fences and I grabbed all I could
The sidewalk I waited
(I waited)
I waited on the sidewalk, for my dad, I mean
But I couldn't find him
He was nowhere to be seenEmbedShare URLCopyEmbedCopy

songs.lyrics:
Take all their islands and they'll play their violins
They heard the songs from nearby continents
Everyone cried​ when they saw with their eyes
The land shift underneath their feet

I was living in the past ‘cause I’ll be dead in the future
The kids from ED, they smelled bad, I had to teach one how to
Unzip his backpack, sitting on my dad’s lap
As he taught me to play piano, but I could only play by ear

Spent his money on whores when he came back from the war
He just needed something pure, and he'd tell me these stories
And one night they stole the boats, went for a smoke on the water

And we march, across, the countryside
We march, across, the countryside

Not by sickness, God, not by sickness
Wanted to find you in a hotel room, elevator shafts
But I’m tired of this honeymoon, bored in the bed with you
My dad called me "fag" even though he had slept with men
I swear that VHS is ingrained in my memory
Just like everything, just the historian
Only comfort I can take, Rome was not forgotten in a day
As we march, across, the countryside
As we march, across, the countryside

Scorched-earth policy
They burned everything as they left
Freezing my legs off in some tent into their hands
God save them all

(I don’t know if it’s just the chord but I can’t really do it well)

Freezing my legs off in some tent into their hands
God save them all

The hair on your head is making me dizzy

Basel, Switzerland

(Or was it 1666?)

songs.lyrics:
As if on cue
They lit a firework
The sky reeled back
And I ran fast to get to you
I think you knew
Before the war began
What loving to run towards something can do to a man

Fall over the edge
Learn to live while falling
Every life is a path worth following
When you put it in words
It's comfortingly bland
There's so little left to understand

When we're strung up, hanging from the knots we've allowed
We call up our angels to cut us down

songs.full_title: Ryan North by Northwest by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: Ryan North by Northwest

description.plain:
The title of this song refers to writer Ryan North and the 1959 thriller film North by Northwest.

Ryan North is a writer who formed the webcomic site Dinosaur Comics and has written several notable comics and graphic novels including the Adventure Time comics and The Unbeatable Squirrel Girl. He’s won the Web Cartoonist’s Choice Awards for Outstanding Anthropomorphic Comic, and earlier in the album on the second track “portrait of the artist as a young fag”, anthropomorphic fiction (or ‘anthro-fiction’) is referenced.

North by Northwest was directed by Alfred Hitchcock and stars Cary Grant. The plot involves a man who is followed by a spy after he’s mistaken for a government agent. It’s considered a classic and is one of Hitchcock’s best-known films.

songs.full_title: What Does OUJ Stand For by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: What Does OUJ Stand For

description.plain:
As of now, we still don’t know for sure what OUJ actually stands for here.
Will Toledo briefly considered re-recording this song for his label debut, Teens of Style. Though that did not happen, it was later reworked into Cosmic Hero, off of 2016’s Teens of Denial.

songs.full_title: You Have to Go to College by Car Seat Headrest
songs.title: You Have to Go to College
songs.title_with_featured: You Have to Go to College

description.plain: The title refers to Animal Collective’s song “College,” which features (exclusively) the line “You don’t have to go to college.” Animal Collective co-leader Avey Tare’s explanation of the line (see the proposed edit to the song bio) illuminates the Car Seat Headrest song, too: like Tare’s, Toledo’s song is concerned with the pressure many young people feel to go to college in order to secure a job, as well as the uncertainty and fear that often characterize the transition out of adolescence.

description.plain:
“Act Suspicious” is one of the two bonus tracks included with the Japanese digital release of Teens of Denial. As of 2017, however, the tracks are no longer available for download.

“Act Suspicious” is a remake of a song from 2 of the same title, featuring a slightly different arrangement and different lyrics.

songs.full_title: 2:24 by Car Seat Headrest

description.plain:
This song is about Marching Band Practice during the final stretch of summer, and how 2:24 PM is the longest minute of the day. This song was intended to start 2 minutes and 24 seconds into “Disjecta Membra” but Will decided against this later.

This song is a remake of a track of the same name that Will had previously made for the album “Katzenjammer”, under the Nervous Young Men band name.
